cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "PEAR: Perceptual Edge Audit for RL in vision-language models"
message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
type: software
authors:
  - family-names: "Dardouri"
    given-names: "Bechir"
repository-code: "https://github.com/Bechirdardouri/PEAR"
abstract: >-
  PEAR is a measurement-first toolkit for reinforcement learning in
  vision-language models. Its central instrument, VEST, computes a
  per-example score g(x) = log p(gold | image, q) − log p(gold | blank, q)
  in two teacher-forced forward passes, and rolls those up to the
  vision-driven fraction (VDF): the share of correct rollouts produced
  on examples where seeing the image actually moved belief toward the
  gold answer. A 2x4 audit grid across Qwen3.5 model scales and four
  public VQA benchmarks shows VDF varies by nearly an order of
  magnitude, contradicting the uniform "perception bottleneck" framing
  of the perception-aware RL sub-literature. A before/after audit on
  the one publicly released perception-aware checkpoint (VGPO) shows
  no measurable VDF shift on out-of-distribution ChartQA.
keywords:
  - vision-language-models
  - reinforcement-learning
  - evaluation
  - interpretability
  - vqa
license: MIT
version: "0.1.0"
date-released: "2026-06-21"
